(44, 10, 15, 45, 14, 14, 14, 'What God hath cleansed', 'Cleansing and Perception of Cleanliness', 'This connection highlights the theme of what is considered clean or unclean. Both passages emphasize that God''s declaration of cleanliness should not be questioned by human standards.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 10, 15, 54, 4, 3, 5, 'What God hath cleansed', 'Cleansing and Sanctification of Food', 'This connection highlights the theme of what God has cleansed and the sanctification of food. Both passages emphasize that God has declared certain things good and acceptable for consumption, reinforcing the idea that believers should not call them common.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 10, 15, 44, 10, 28, 28, 'that call not thou common', 'God''s Cleansing and Acceptance', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s cleansing and acceptance of all people. Both passages emphasize that what God has cleansed should not be considered common or unclean.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 10, 16, 1, 41, 32, 32, NULL, 'Establishment of Divine Purpose', 'This connection highlights the repetition in both passages, emphasizing the certainty of God''s actions. In Acts, the vision is repeated thrice, while in Genesis, the doubling of the dream signifies God''s established plan.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 10, 16, 43, 21, 17, 17, 'thrice', 'Connection of Threefold Repetition', 'This connection highlights the significance of the number three in both passages. In Acts, the vision is repeated thrice, while in John, Jesus asks Peter three times if he loves Him, emphasizing restoration and affirmation.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 10, 16, 47, 13, 1, 1, 'this was done thrice', 'Witnesses and Repetition', 'This connection highlights the theme of repetition as a means of establishing truth. In Acts, the vision is repeated thrice, while in 2 Corinthians, Paul emphasizes the importance of multiple witnesses for validation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 10, 17, 43, 13, 12, 12, NULL, 'Understanding Divine Revelation', 'This connection highlights the theme of understanding divine actions. In Acts, Peter is uncertain about the meaning of a vision, while in John, Jesus prompts the disciples to comprehend the significance of his actions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 10, 17, 44, 2, 12, 12, NULL, 'Doubt and Inquiry in Acts', 'Both passages emphasize a sense of doubt and inquiry regarding divine revelations. In Acts 10:17, Peter is in doubt about the meaning of his vision, while in Acts 2:12, the people are in doubt about the events they witness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 10, 17, 44, 5, 24, 24, 'doubted in himself', 'Doubt and Inquiry in Acts', 'This connection highlights the theme of doubt present in both passages. Peter''s internal questioning in Acts 10:17 parallels the uncertainty expressed by the high priest and others in Acts 5:24.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 10, 17, 44, 9, 43, 43, 'Simonâ€™s house', 'Peter''s Stay in Joppa', 'Both passages emphasize Peter''s presence in Joppa, linking his stay with the unfolding events involving Cornelius. The mention of Simon''s house in both contexts highlights the significance of Peter''s location during this pivotal moment.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 10, 17, 44, 10, 3, 3, NULL, 'Vision and Divine Communication', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine communication through visions. Both passages involve significant visions where God conveys messages to Peter and Cornelius, emphasizing the importance of these revelations in the unfolding narrative.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 10, 17, 60, 1, 11, 11, 'doubted in himself what this vision', 'Connection of Searching and Meaning', 'This connection highlights the theme of searching for understanding. In Acts, Peter is ''doubting in himself'' about the meaning of his vision, while in 1 Peter, the prophets are ''searching what'' the Spirit signifies regarding Christ''s sufferings and glory.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
